and understand the logic here,

120
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:51,100
I think the best way

121
00:02:51,100 --> 00:02:52,699
is to take everyone to quickly look at

122
00:02:52,699 --> 00:02:53,666
the eight major battles that the Federal Reserve has experienced

123
00:02:53,666 --> 00:02:55,566
in the past century,

124
00:02:55,566 --> 00:02:56,966
his own "War of Independence",

125
00:02:56,966 --> 00:02:58,133
and then we will analyse 

126
00:02:58,133 --> 00:02:59,999
how Trump might deal with Powell.

127
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:01,233
I tell you, it's very interesting.

128
00:03:01,233 --> 00:03:02,766
Let's begin.

129
00:03:04,166 --> 00:03:06,833
1913, the U.S. Congress passed the Federal Reserve Act.

130
00:03:06,833 --> 00:03:08,166
A central bank composed

131
00:03:08,166 --> 00:03:09,566
of 12 reserve banks,

132
00:03:09,566 --> 00:03:11,033
the Federal Reserve, was established

133
00:03:11,866 --> 00:03:14,166
The law stipulates that it is "independent but supervised"

134
00:03:14,166 --> 00:03:15,500
It can independently implement monetary policy

135
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:16,166
but at this time

136
00:03:16,166 --> 00:03:17,833
its independence was only theoretical 

137
00:03:17,833 --> 00:03:18,799
The early monetary policy

138
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:21,100
basically had to cooperate with the needs of department of treasury

139
00:03:21,100 --> 00:03:22,300
Generally speaking,

140
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:23,333
if the full score of independence is 10,

141
00:03:23,333 --> 00:03:24,599
I would give it 5 points

142
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:25,600
It still fail

143
00:03:25,600 --> 00:03:28,233
Soon the Federal Reserve ushered in its first battle,

144
00:03:28,233 --> 00:03:30,700
which was the gold war in the 1930s.

145
00:03:31,566 --> 00:03:32,699
When the Federal Reserve was first established,

146
00:03:32,699 --> 00:03:34,366
the United States implemented the gold standard.

147
00:03:34,366 --> 00:03:36,300
The law required that for every dollar issued, you

148
00:03:36,300 --> 00:03:38,699
must have 40% gold as support.

149
00:03:38,699 --> 00:03:39,433
So the Federal Reserve

150
00:03:39,433 --> 00:03:41,500
is actually a bit like an ultimate gold merchant.

151
00:03:41,500 --> 00:03:42,500
How much gold you have

152
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:44,033
is equivalent to how much money you print.

153
00:03:45,100 --> 00:03:47,666
Although the gold standard sounds very reasonable

154
00:03:47,666 --> 00:03:49,100
and strictly limits the issuance of currency

155
00:03:49,100 --> 00:03:51,033
there is actually a very serious problem here. 

156
00:03:51,033 --> 00:03:52,433
The problem is that it forces the Fed

157
00:03:52,433 --> 00:03:54,566
to tighten its monetary policy when the economy is in a recession,

158
00:03:54,566 --> 00:03:56,533
which intensifies the magnitude of economic shocks.

159
00:03:57,266 --> 00:03:59,066
When the Great Depression broke out in 1929,

160
00:03:59,066 --> 00:04:00,766
people kept looking for banks to exchange their gold.

161
00:04:00,766 --> 00:04:03,166
The Fed's gold reserves

162
00:04:03,166 --> 00:04:04,666
plummeted from $4.5 billion to $3.2 billion,

163
00:04:04,666 --> 00:04:06,800
which greatly limited its ability to issue currency.

164
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:09,199
At the height of the crisis when stimulus policies were most needed,

165
00:04:09,199 --> 00:04:10,666
the Fed was restricted and had

166
00:04:10,666 --> 00:04:11,500
to tighten its monetary policy . 

167
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:12,699
So at the White House

168
00:04:12,699 --> 00:04:14,366
President Roosevelt took the lead and

169
00:04:14,366 --> 00:04:16,800
promulgated the Gold Reserve Act in 1934. 

170
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:17,899
After the gold standard was abandoned,

171
00:04:17,899 --> 00:04:19,566
the dollar was no longer backed by gold. 

172
00:04:19,566 --> 00:04:20,666
At the same time gold was nationalised and

173
00:04:20,666 --> 00:04:22,100
all citizens had to hand in their gold.

174
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:24,300
The key point was that the object of his handing in gold was not the Federal Reserve

175
00:04:24,300 --> 00:04:25,866
but the U.S. Treasury Department.

176
00:04:25,866 --> 00:04:28,066
He also required the Federal Reserve to give the vast majority of its gold

177
00:04:28,066 --> 00:04:29,399
to the Treasury Department.

178
00:04:30,733 --> 00:04:31,766
Once this move was made, 

179
00:04:31,766 --> 00:04:33,333
on the one hand, the Federal Reserve's functions in gold

180
00:04:33,333 --> 00:04:34,666
were almost completely taken back.

181
00:04:34,666 --> 00:04:35,300
On the other hand,

182
00:04:35,300 --> 00:04:36,199
the Federal Reserve could control the discount rate

183
00:04:36,199 --> 00:04:37,799
in terms of monetary policy.

184
00:04:37,800 --> 00:04:39,766
Basically, the Treasury Department had to give

185
00:04:39,766 --> 00:04:41,766
priority to meeting the demand for treasury bond issuance, which

186
00:04:41,766 --> 00:04:43,533
basically completely undermined the Federal Reserve.

187
00:04:43,533 --> 00:04:45,699
The then Chairman of the Federal Reserve later recalled and joked

188
00:04:45,699 --> 00:04:48,099
that although he was nominally the Chairman of the Central Bank,

189
00:04:48,100 --> 00:04:48,766
he was actually

190
00:04:48,766 --> 00:04:49,533
just an

191
00:04:49,533 --> 00:04:51,000
assistant to the Treasury Department

192
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,066
doing some very basic administrative work.

193
00:04:55,766 --> 00:04:56,299
Soon after that

194
00:04:56,300 --> 00:04:57,533
World War II came.

195
00:04:57,533 --> 00:04:58,533
In order to cope with the war,

196
00:04:58,533 --> 00:05:00,533
the Federal Reserve lost even its superficial independence.

197
00:05:00,533 --> 00:05:02,566
The Treasury Department basically forced him

198
00:05:02,566 --> 00:05:03,199
to sign an agreement

199
00:05:03,199 --> 00:05:05,333
requiring the Federal Reserve to purchase Treasury bonds at a very low interest rate

200
00:05:05,333 --> 00:05:07,066
of less than 2.5%

201
00:05:07,066 --> 00:05:08,299
to help the Treasury Department raise funds.

202
00:05:08,300 --> 00:05:10,000
So you see, during this period,

203
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:10,866
although the Federal Reserve

204
00:05:10,866 --> 00:05:12,533
was still an independent central bank in name

205
00:05:12,533 --> 00:05:13,399
it was actually

206
00:05:13,399 --> 00:05:15,299
a subsidiary of the Treasury Department.

207
00:05:15,300 --> 00:05:17,233
The Fed lost the gold war and

208
00:05:17,233 --> 00:05:19,066
its independence score was 2 points.

209
00:05:21,300 --> 00:05:22,199
Originally, after World War II,

210
00:05:22,199 --> 00:05:23,666
the Fed should have been more independent

211
00:05:23,666 --> 00:05:24,600
and stopped backing up the Treasury Department

212
00:05:24,600 --> 00:05:26,800
However, the US government was about to start the Korean War,

213
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:27,733
and the government still needed money.

214
00:05:27,733 --> 00:05:28,966
President Truman still wanted

215
00:05:28,966 --> 00:05:31,533
to continue the model of the Fed printing money and buying treasury bonds.

216
00:05:31,533 --> 00:05:33,333
Well, this time the Fed stood its ground

217
00:05:33,333 --> 00:05:34,699
After all, because it had printed too much money before,

218
00:05:34,699 --> 00:05:36,499
the inflation in the United States had exceeded 9%

219
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:37,066
If it continued like this,

220
00:05:37,066 --> 00:05:38,466
the economy would really be in trouble.

221
00:05:38,466 --> 00:05:40,099
So the Fed said no, no,

222
00:05:40,100 --> 00:05:41,533
and it did not agree to Truman's request.

223
00:05:41,533 --> 00:05:43,699
After several very difficult negotiations,

224
00:05:43,699 --> 00:05:44,766
the then Secretary of the Treasury,

225
00:05:44,766 --> 00:05:46,133
who was also a good friend of Truman

226
00:05:46,133 --> 00:05:47,066
used a shady trick.

227
00:05:47,066 --> 00:05:48,399
He did not communicate with the Fed

228
00:05:48,399 --> 00:05:50,466
but directly gave a public speech in January 1951

229
00:05:50,466 --> 00:05:50,933
saying that the Federal Reserve

230
00:05:50,933 --> 00:05:53,399
had agreed to the Treasury's treasury bond purchase plan.

231
00:05:53,399 --> 00:05:55,099
When the Chairman of the Federal Reserve heard it, he became anxious and

232
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:56,333
asked, "When did I agree to it?"

233
00:05:56,333 --> 00:05:57,666
The contradiction between both sides intensified.

234
00:05:57,666 --> 00:05:59,866
After all, the Fed is still independent in law

235
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:01,566
and has some capital to be tough.

236
00:06:01,566 --> 00:06:01,933
He said that

237
00:06:01,933 --> 00:06:04,266
if Treasury Department still has such a tough attitude,

238
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:05,399
our policies

239
00:06:05,399 --> 00:06:07,199
will be completely independent in the future,

240
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:08,566
there is no room for negotiation.

241
00:06:08,566 --> 00:06:09,933
After a month of fierce public conflict,

242
00:06:09,933 --> 00:06:11,466
the Treasury finally

243
00:06:11,466 --> 00:06:12,599
gave in.

244
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:13,699
The Fed and the Treasury

245
00:06:13,699 --> 00:06:16,466
signed the famous 1951 Monetary Agreement.

246
00:06:16,466 --> 00:06:17,199
The Treasury agreed that

247
00:06:17,199 --> 00:06:19,333
the Fed would no longer purchase Treasury bonds at a fixed interest rate

248
00:06:19,333 --> 00:06:20,699
The market generally believed that

249
00:06:20,699 --> 00:06:22,866
the real independence of the modern Federal Reserve

250
00:06:22,866 --> 00:06:24,866
began with this 1951 agreement.

251
00:06:24,866 --> 00:06:26,800
The Fed won the independence battle

252
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:28,366
with an independence score of 6 points.

253
00:06:31,033 --> 00:06:32,333
As the price of the negotiation,

254
00:06:32,333 --> 00:06:34,533
the chairman of the Fed resigned.

255
00:06:34,533 --> 00:06:35,266
He was replaced by

256
00:06:35,266 --> 00:06:36,133
an assistant secretary of

257
00:06:36,133 --> 00:06:37,933
the Treasury who was in charge of negotiations at the time

258
00:06:37,933 --> 00:06:39,033
His name was William Martin.

259
00:06:39,033 --> 00:06:40,466
Remember this name, it's very important.

260
00:06:40,466 --> 00:06:40,933
You see,

261
00:06:40,933 --> 00:06:42,266
the Treasury had a good idea.

262
00:06:42,266 --> 00:06:44,299
I would place one of my own in the Federal Reserve

263
00:06:44,300 --> 00:06:45,899
so that even if I signed the agreement, 

264
00:06:45,899 --> 00:06:47,599
could cooperate on policy.

265
00:06:47,600 --> 00:06:48,866
But they didn't expect that

266
00:06:48,866 --> 00:06:50,333
the so-called "one of their own"

267
00:06:50,333 --> 00:06:51,533
they placed in the Federal Reserve

268
00:06:51,533 --> 00:06:53,733
would become the founder of the Federal Reserve's independence

269
00:06:53,733 --> 00:06:54,966
and served nearly 20 years

270
00:06:54,966 --> 00:06:56,899
and is the longest-serving chairman in history.

271
00:06:56,899 --> 00:06:57,933
A building of the Federal Reserve

272
00:06:57,933 --> 00:06:59,266
is named after him. 

273
00:07:00,733 --> 00:07:01,500
Let me talk a little about

274
00:07:01,500 --> 00:07:02,366
William Martin .

